name "sec:Scarcity"

\end_inset

Measures for Scarcity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Heffetz finds that the degree to which people notice items explains the
 corresponding (permanent) income elasticities better.
 This observation has provided the basis for inspection of visible consumption
 in many studies thereforth.
 In an environment of inequalities, however, it is likely that i) the items
 available to higher status individuals may never be accessible to lower
 status individuals and ii) the individuals with perceived higher status
 may notice items differently from how the lower status individuals might
 notice them.
 The social factors thus relevant for the difference in visible preferences
 are sought in the studies on visible consumption in the developing countries.
 In India, these factors are religion and caste - while in South Africa
 and United States, race seems to have significance.
 The developing countries may also offer a less consumerist and less individuali
stic agrarian environment where expenditure is more visible than in a relatively
 more individualistic and industrialized society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
For visibility to bear significance in an environment of severe inequalities
 and scarcities, an association with higher income becomes relevant.
 Khamis et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"

\end_inset

 therefore perform a slightly more detailed survey by asking what an individual
 whose consumption is noticed would do when her income rises (by 20%).
 This quantifies the expectations from others associates the total expenditure
 with higher-income.
 The items where consumers expect the consumption to rise with increased
 income are those that associate with higher income and are declared 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conspicuous
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the study.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
In a developing economy, the criterion for status consumption is clearly
 not just noticeability any more.
 Visible consumption may detail the mechanics of status competitions in
 a narrow sense where consumers participate in a market to increase their
 perceived status - but it does not provide an adequate picture of status
 consumption.
 One reason is that markets are underdeveloped in the developing world and
 social status is largely yielded through economic classes and social strata.
 The second - and probably more significant - reason is that status signaling
 does not exist in a society as an inherent need for visible appeal amongst
 humans.
 Instead visible consumption matters because of an item being associated
 with a higher status (in the sense which Veblen had talked about in his
 19th century treatise
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The association of visibility with status is therefore essential to conspicuous
 consumption.
 In fact, Veblen's assertion that conspicuous goods are essentially futile
 happens to be helpful in ensuring the separability of the visible/status
 utility.
 By assuming that a visible (or conspicuous) good serves no utility other
 than of status, we can be that the item in consideration does not have
 any utilitarian value and combine all the products to talk about the status
 benefit that the consumer receives.
 The separability criterion unfortunately is not observed in all the literature
 around conspicuous consumption.
 It may be easy to claim that watches and make-up don't serve any utility
 other than status but it's difficult argue or measure how clear the status
 benefits from housing or shoes are.
 If the assumption of conspicuous goods being completely futile from a utilitari
an perspective is relieved, then combining the visible goods (as has been
 done in a lot of literature) is problematic (Corneo et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

 skillfully us this assumption for a simple model for signaling).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The view of status consumption we consider relevant for developing economies
 relies on Hirsch's idea of scarcity.
 We argue that status and scarcity of items must go hand in hand in a study
 of conspicuous consumption.
 Instead of limiting ourselves to visible consumption as the particular
 mechanics of status signaling - where consumers buy items in a common market
 and (presumably) over-weigh on items that are more noticeable - we attempt
 to understand the reasons behind status-signaling by looking at the differences
 in patterns between the richer and poorer sections of society and attempt
 to understand how unavailability of items (scarcity) as well as disparities
 of services across regions and classes in a society are reflected in both
 price and consumption of commodities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
This is not to discount a study of visible consumption or the importance
 of a visibility survey in any way.
 In fact, visible consumption that affects status competitions encompasses
 more than just scarcity - but there are severe measurement issues with
 the visibility of many status goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Before we attempt to measure just how scarce an item is, we must clarify
 the definition of scarcity for our purposes.
 Scarcity can be a confusing term since it encompasses both a so-called
 physical scarcity (unavailability) and the perceived scarcity (what we
 feel as scarce).
 For simplicity, we assume that all felt scarcities are physically scarce
 - or else consumers would acquire the item that is meant to be physically
 scarce.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 denotes the felt scarcities and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 the direct physical scarcities, then for our assertion 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subset S$
\end_inset

 doesn't make sense until we extend our notion of physical scarcity to include
 the barriers in society that may cause felt scarcities 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Instead of attempting to define or measure felt scarcities 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 themselves, we expand the notion of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to include barriers created through status competitions, advertising or
 other social-psychological communication than create the sense of urgent
 demand for a commodity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The perceptions of quality of life are entities that cannot be measured
 easily but still may qualify as felt scarcities.
 Our simplifying assumption allows us to look for parameters that can affect
 the demand for status items better.
 We surmise that conditions of availability, price and the rush (congestion)
 towards a new item must encompass all what we consider as barriers to a
 possession of an asset.
 The barriers of availability and price are relatively easy to measure -
 but the measurement of flocking towards an item - requires a formulation
 of status utility.
 We find such barriers - artificial or social - as a probabilistic concern
 which we discuss later in the study.
 The essential idea is that a commodity can indicate status through either
 being a snob type (where it has already been associated with high-status
 individuals in the past) or by being a bandwagon type item (where there
 is a clear competition to achieve a new item) 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If everybody has a certain item, then consumers may not consider it so important
 to acquire the item (since everyone else already has it) whereas for other
 types of item, consumers may rush to the item solely because there is a
 trend amongst everybody else to acquire.
 These are the snob and bandwagon types of item considered in the literature
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

.
 Researchers have used an extended social-means model to measure these in
 experiments
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gierl_scarcity"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
In summary, if the item is affordable and available, it should not be considered
 physically scarce - while if it has had a trend of consumers flocking to
 it - then it would feel as scarce.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\size large
Measuring Status Consumption in a Developing Economy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
To measure positional consumption one can either split the consumer basket
 into positional and non-positional items or assign a status-utility to
 every commodity in the basket.
 For reasons cited in sub-section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Status-as-lagged-consumption"

\end_inset

, we choose the latter option.
 The criterion of classification of a status item (or assignment of such
 the status carrying power to every item) is inspired by Hirsch's notion
 of congestion - a herding of consumers to the desired commodity that drives
 scarcities and status consumption
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing single
The difference between physical and social scarcities is not considered
 relevant (a clarification on the notion of scarcity is provided in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Scarcity"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The criterion employed in assigning a status 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

advantage
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of an item is the difference in prices (wherever available) of an item
 in the market.
 The more price differentiation exists, higher is the likelihood for the
 consumers to indicate status through purchase of higher priced item.
 Indeed, we rely on our claim that a consumer can indicate higher status
 by choosing the higher priced variety of an item.
 For items that are physically scarce, the price differences between commodities
 is less likely (although still possible due to distribution and storage
 costs involved) and every product whose varieties exists with different
 prices in a market is potentially a status good.
 In this simple formulation of status, therefore, prices (inferred or directly
 observed) are exogenous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since price is the simplest of all barriers to acquiring an item, a rough
 estimate of the price of an item may be a good indicator of whether that
 item can exhibit any status or not.
 Unfortunately, a detailed price information for all products is not available
 in consumption data.
 Relying on total quantity (
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

) consumed of an item or the expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $(e=q\cdot p)$
\end_inset

 on the item can obfuscate the sense of status consumption.
 If a consumer accumulates cheaper varieties of the an item instead of accumulat
ing the higher priced varieties of the item, the comparison of quantities
 would no longer provide an accurate representation of the status-related
 consumption.
 To illustrate with an example, if the prices of an item are 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2}(where\ p_{1}>p_{2})$
\end_inset

 - which can be consumed by 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\cdot q_{A}<p_{2}\cdot q_{B}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{A}<e_{B})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{A}<q_{B}$
\end_inset

, consumer B accumulates cheaper varieties of the item.
 If we don't observe 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2}$
\end_inset

 directly but instead of total consumption on the item by 
\begin_inset Formula $A(=e_{A})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, then even 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{A}<e_{B}$
\end_inset

 does not necessarily imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 derives less status than 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 by consuming the variants of the same item.
 The status utility may not be the same for the two variants of the item
 with different prices.
 The choice of prices are therefore important (unless every variant of the
 item with a different price is treated as a separate item).
 In absence of observed prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2}$
\end_inset

, one can instead estimate prices as 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{A}/q_{A}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{B}/q_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 These prices (direct or inferred) must then be compare the richer quantiles
 of the population consume.
 Given our lagged asset view of status, we assert that whether a consumer
 accumulating cheaper varieties of an item gets more status than another
 consumer status depends on whether the consumers with higher assets (and
 thus higher status) also spend on the higher-priced varieties or not.
 More simply put, whether the higher priced variety of an item can indicate
 more status than a cheaper variety or not depends on how many people already
 above that person in the order of status or asset possession already have
 that item.
 For every consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and item 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, the (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}-max(p_{k})$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula $\times q_{i}$
\end_inset

 (negative by definition) can give us a rough estimate of the status that
 the consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 may derive from the item.
 We can call this the 
\series bold
affordability
\series default
 factor for further reference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that participation of consumers in the same market is key in the
 above argument of price differences.
 Certain items may have higher price varieties due to transport costs -
 so if the markets where consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 participate are affected by different supply-side issues then it would
 erroneous to consider status differences on grounds of price differences
 observed by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 All supply-side issues can be considered another barrier to status (which
 can either improve or affect status).
 By being in a region, neighborhood or social network where certain commodities
 are exclusively available, a consumer may be imparted status advantage
 (or disadvantage).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The emergence of new commodities is worth comment - since a new commodity
 that is not traditionally guarded by social networks may appear to change
 old barriers to status.
 The status advantage of a new commodity should also be explained by the
 affordability factor ( i.e.
 the commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}-max(p_{k})\cdot q$
\end_inset

).
 Electronic goods, cars, education or media could fall under this category
 of items.
 If we continue to assume that the market would be able to price a status
 commodity fairly (i.e.
 the new items introduced would have a price reflecting their status power).
 then we may treat the new entrant as a higher priced variety of an existing
 item category.
 While this may sound convincing, one cannot rule out instances where prices
 don't accurately represent the status benefits of the new item.
 That the market is able to set a fair price on a new entrant is a strong
 assumption 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A practical consideration is that for us to apply the affordability factor
 we also have to set the old categories of items generic enough to accommodate
 a new item as a higher price variant of a category.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In reality, a new entrant may take years to develop into a status product
 and could be a result of price changes as well as introduction of new products
 (possibly of lower quality) to let consumers subscribe to the item.
 The equilibrium value would be where the individuals are priced out of
 an item whose selling price can no longer be lowered with innovation.
 These are supply/firm concerns but matter if prices can no longer be considered
 as an accurate representation of status.
 Considering prices as exogenous, the only correction we apply is by observing
 the existing status of the consumer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A new commodity - after all - is often priced lower to attract customers.
 The status advantage of the new item thus introduced may be slightly lower
 when the item introduced is sufficiently lower in price (we assume that
 price represents quality).
 One may thus need a correction to the term 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}-max(p_{k})\cdot q$
\end_inset

 so that it reflects the status demand in addition to price difference.
 Since we're interested in the status utility of the new item, we can once
 again use the observation that the status advantage of an item is dependent
 on the status of individuals who already have access to it (or would have
 easier access to it).
 A new entrant in the market may be limited to exclusive social sections
 or be priced high enough to prevent lower income consumers from acquiring
 it - just the same as other items are.
 Let's assume there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 clusters in a society that are sorted by their income and asset ownership
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}>i_{2}>...>i_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 If all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 clusters observe the launch of a new product (e.g.
 a new phone category or a car), then we can consider a case such all sections
 with income rank lower than 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{k}$
\end_inset

 would not have access to the new product.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such cases possible and we can argue that not only would the market put
 a high price on the new entrant but might be compelled to introduce substitutes
 of the new entrant if 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is low (i.e.
 close to the lowest rank 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{n}$
\end_inset

).
 The advantage is still AF (without any correction related to existing status).
 If the consumer cannot access this item then the status advantage is clearly
 0.
 In this model, the status advantage is proportional to the price differences.
 One may require a slight adjustment of the difference formula of AF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider a numerical example.
 Let there be high, middle, low classes and two variants being sold as 10,20
 - which are accessible to high, middle.
 If middle classes consume 10, high classes 20, then the affordability factor
 becomes {-20q,-10q,0}.
 Now if a new commodity is introduced at 15, then only high class has access
 to it.
 If someone in high class or middle class switches to 15 then the AF becomes
 -5q instead of 0,-10q respectively (if all high classes together move to
 15 then 20 would be out of the market and the AF would remain 0).
 Now if a new commodity in the same category is introduced at 5 then everybody
 has access to it and the new distribution may be {-15q, -10q, 0} (assuming
 middle class and high class consume 10 and 20 respectively).
 The apparent 5q improvement for the lowest class could in fact amount to
 zero in reality.
 This the status is therefore just one-direction.
 Consumption increases for the new item but it doesn't sustain because the
 status advantage is minimal in the long-run.
 However, in the short-run the status advantage may be huge if the consumers
 haven't had the item for a long time (forcing the market to bring new status
 items with higher price).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, while the standard deviations away from the mean average expenditure
 may gives us a rough estimate of the status advantage associated with the
 item, we must continue to understand the segmentation in society that excludes
 a certain region or section of society from consuming certain items.
 The other correction...Notice that we don't use budget ratios 
\begin_inset Formula $(q/x)$
\end_inset

 in the analysis so far.
 This is because status determinants - i.e.
 assets and barriers must on consumption total consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 if an item has multiple prices) rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}/x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (which only matter for budgeting concerns).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:AvAfBa"

\end_inset

 Measuring Availability and Affordability 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Scarcity is far too abstract an idea to measure - hence we consider a few
 parameters that may contribute to perceived scarcities.
 First, we assign a higher status value of a good in a wider region based
 on its consumption pattern in a smaller area where it is available and
 consumed - an item that is available in a smaller section of the population
 carries more status (all else being equal) than an item which is available
 to all (this view is inspired by both Veblen and Hirsch).
 In the developing countries, the issue of 
\series bold
availability
\series default
 is particularly relevant since rural areas are faced with unavailability
 of services and goods that are available (although limited) in the urban
 areas
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing single
This unavailability can spiral into severe demand pressures through pressures
 on urban migration.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In the data from Tanzania, for example, we find not only that the region
 dummies are significant in consumption of certain items in the survey (particul
arly with respect to such as electricity which is completely unavailable
 in large parts of the country), but the availability of electricity seems
 to transform the income elasticities of demand for other expenditures as
 well (e.g.
 marriage).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, a consumer also indicates status by choosing higher priced varieties
 of the item.
  If there is price differentiation in the market, all items that exhibit
 higher prices can provide status benefits to the user.
 This is encompassed in the idea of 
\series bold
affordability
\series default
 of the item (a statement of price of the item).
 While the difference in prices does bring some empirical issues - since
 it is not always clear whether one should treat the higher priced variety
 of the item as a separate item.
 To resolve this issue, we use the standard utility decomposition used in
 the survey (food, entertainment, housing etc.).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Lastly, other than price-budget concerns (affordability) and issues of supply
 (availability), a status-signaling can be tracked by an item's demand in
 the richer sections of the society.
 Highly popular items (i.e.
 items with higher number of purchasers of the item in the population of
 consumers) can drive the appeal of the item down or up.
 Items like jewelry and luxury cars are those that cannot become extremely
 popular.
 If such items were to become popular, then the richer consumers would rush
 to something else that indicates their higher status.
 These items are known as snob items.
 Items which people rush to purchase - on the other hand - are called bandwagon
 items.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
It is worth emphasizing that in a market where product differentiation exists,
 items can change from snob type to bandwagon type (or vice versa) over
 time.
 Items like new electronics are snob items when they're not affordable -
 but as they become more affordable with time they become bandwagon items.
 As consumers rush to them, they get replaced by a new snob item in the
 market.
  The effect of popularity of an item on to its demand can thus be in either
 direction i.e.
 limited supply would mean a higher appeal for snob items but high supply
 would mean less appeal.
 A time-series of expenditures can help us understand the trend in rushing
 towards certain items.
 The degree to which consumers rush to an item is termed as the 
\series bold
bandwagon effect
\series default
 - which too carries the status weight for a item
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing single
The snob or bandwagon effects must be seen in combination with affordability
 and availability.
 If the item is available and not affordable - then the price and budget
 constraints are more important than the bandwagon characteristics of the
 item.
 The snob or bandwagon nature of the item matters for an individual consumer
 only when it is affordable (thus potentially popular) as well as available.
 This is in accordance with the discussion in Section i.e.
 all direct physical scarcities are perceived scarcities.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The parameters availability, affordability and the bandwagon affect allow
 for a sorting order of all items in terms of status.
 Availability encompasses all issues that put an item in the market.
 Regional and supply-side issues thus affect availability.
 In absence of the data on supply of the items, we assign availability as
 a binary variable which is set to true in a region when the item appears
 in the consumption data for the region.
 Affordability, on the other hand, sums up price-related concerns on the
 demand-side.
 An item is affordable solely based on the price of the average consumption
 unit in the analysis of data.
 Further, the the bandwagon effect measures the effect of popularity of
 an item which may increase or decrease the consumption of an item based
 on to what extent an item is a bandwagon type item.
 An individual is likely to lose interest in a particular jewelry product
 if it the latter is available and affordable to everybody.
 In the Hirschian terminology
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"

\end_inset

, a physical scarcity is only realized by the availability of an item while
 social scarcities are realised through affordability and popularity.
\end_layout

