 than prices or quantities).
 Semantically, affordability is a statement of price in the market and should
 be calculated from the average price of the item.
 Thus, the total expenditure and the unit quantity
\series bold
 
\series default
of the item (consumed on average) is all what one may need to measure affordabil
ity.
 In absence of the average quantity consumed, we can approximate the quantity
 by scaling the consumption with household size.
 The price of the unit quantity (or the scaled average cost) relative to
 the average total expenditure gives us a measure of affordability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
As an example, to answer whether AC is more affordable than electricity
 (the two are compared only to stress that any two commodities can be compared
 based on the criterion), we use the ratio of the average cost of AC in
 the population of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 consumers (i.e.
 for item 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 amongst total  number of items the average price as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N}\Sigma_{n=1}^{N}\frac{q_{i}}{\Sigma_{k,n}^{K}q_{k,n}}$
\end_inset

 ) relative to the average total expenditure .
